In the field of [[fluid dynamics]]  the point at which the [[boundary layer]] changes from [[Laminar flow|laminar]] to [[turbulent]] is called the '''transition point'''. Where the boundary layer becomes turbulent, [[Drag (physics)|drag]] due to [[skin friction]] is relatively high. As speed increases, the upper surface [[laminar–turbulent transition|transition]] point tends to move forward. As the [[angle of attack]] increases, the upper surface transition point also tends to move forward.

{{DEFAULTSORT:Transition Point}}
[[Category:Boundary layers]]


{{Fluiddynamics-stub}}
Behind the transition point in a boundary layer the mean speed and friction drag increases.
